An employee being charged or convicted with a criminal offence is not in itself a reason for disciplinary action. The Company will consider whether the offence or alleged offence is one that makes the employee unsuitable for their type of work. Therefore, the Company will establish the facts of the case and consider whether the facts warrant starting the disciplinary procedure. Similarly, an employee cannot be dismissed solely because they were absent from work as a result of being remanded in custody.

Gross Misconduct

In the event that an employee commits an act of gross misconduct, the Company is entitled to summarily terminate the employees contract of employment without notice or pay in lieu of notice. 

The following non-exhaustive list gives examples of offences that the Company will normally regard as gross misconduct:

Theft, fraud, dishonesty or deliberate falsification of records;

Fighting, assault or other violent behaviour;
